Just a fun deck to see, if other types than machines can match together as one toolbox...and if fossil-cards can be used outside adamancipator builds.

We mix lots of GY-effects with various milling-options to setup grave (and field) and use our pseudo-miraclefusion "Fossilfusion" to reuse materials for mighty, but mostly battlephase-related, fusion monsters.

Short description of the engines:

- Mathematician and Rescue Rabbit are our normal summons für milling or a rank 4 (potential OTK with Utopia Double)

- The insects swarm, fill the grave and remove monsters and beargram is a board wipe

- Vernusylphs mill and special monsters from grave,  as well as the dragon ruler

- the Rocks are used for the Fossilfusion or Rank-4s

- Gallis for random mills, Dotscaper as extender, Adhara as special summon and tuner for Natbeast and Kaijus for...kaijuing

-Extra Deck can be adapted to preferences (but Vernusylphs lock out of non-earth-effects!), i decided only to play the Fossil-Monsters that are summoned easily and don't depent too much on our opponents grave.

 

Go second, draw a 6th card and hope for your opponent not to play Makrocosmos or Gravekeepers...
FUTURE PROJECT (NOBLE KNIGHT) - 2024

deck_excerpt: Even nearly a year later, Spright Runick remains as powerful and effective as ever vs. the Masterduel meta!
deck_description:
Even nearly a year later, Spright Runick remains as powerful and effective as ever vs. the Masterduel meta! With the addition of Promethean Princess for an even better grindgame, Spright Runick is as unstoppable as ever!

The ridiculously strong combination of Spright and Runick's smothering control and endless grind game create a deck that all strategies would have to fear and respect. Sprights ending on 3-5 interruptions (Sprind's bounce, Red's monster negate, Carrot's S/T negate, Smasher's banish, and I:P Masquerena's quick link) combined with Runick's draw 3 and multiple quick play spells generally stop any deck cold in their tracks. Both archetypes combined have a potential 10+ interruptions for your opponent to slog through, while maintaining a superior resource loop - outpacing most other strategies!

If you want to win and reach Masters 1 in Masterduel with a relentlessly strong resource-oriented control strategy, you've chosen to pilot the correct deck!

If you want a detailed guide on how to pilot this deck, check out my article from a couple last year.

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

Burn Decks have always been a strange thing in Yugioh. There clearly cards designed for them and play at such a different access to other decks. I think most of the reputation built on trap decks is simply due to price. Many people have to spend ludicrous amounts of money and a whole bunch of hours on their decks only for it to suddenly have no way to play around a deck that's half the price that simply wasn't considered. (On some level I think that was designed with that in mind. I mean what would be a greater deterrent to building a budget deck than to be constantly lambasted by the community for playing the only deck you can afford. But that's just my conspirational thinking) However there is a level of empowerment felt when you take a bunch of terrible commons together to use their unique effects to overcome the odds and win in a new way your opponent could have expected. So dont feel bad for playing a deck with an alternate win-con, feel bad for the poor players who were pier pressured into paying over $1,000 for $15 prizing and bragging rights at a run-down local.

Any here's what most players call Nurse Burn. This deck uses Darklord Nurse Reficule and Bad Reaction to Simochi to transform all of your healing traps into burn traps. So long as you have any combination of 3 of the trap cards set you can easily K.O on the subsequent turn of your opponent's draw step. I am not as familiar with side decks with burn cards as I am with most other decks, but I assume it establishes powerful board breakers as your opponent will likely opt to make you go second. I'm mostly using the side deck to showcase Condemned Witch. It has some unique search effects with the forbidden items which each individually have really powerful effects and can Lonefire blossom itself into Darklord Nurse Reficule.
Flower Cardian Character Deck

In modern YGO stun and solely-burn reliant versions of timelord decks are ineffective and slow. The most effective way to play the timelords is to take advantage of their non-destructive properties to reliably wipe out opponent's boards with no prejudice.

A few points to consider:

>Michion+A special summoned Sandaion+Summon into Gustav is an easy OTK/potentially FTK

>TA.I strike can easliy wreck your opponent off 6000LP if you attack their boss monsters with raphion.

>This deck is not reliant upon its extra deck at all except for the trains but they are an option.

>Interrupted kaiju slumber reliably burns your opponent for 1100 and gives you a 3.3K beater each time.

>The one-off timelords can all be exchanged for extra michion copies. However, I have found michion to be lesss useful late-game.

>Rarely, I have found this deck to suffer from lack of ability to bring back time maiden when banished/in the GY, which is why the deck is supplemented with playsets of piri-reis and celestial transformation. In drawn-out matches, ritual sanctuary (light of redemption/miraculous descent is another consideration) remedies this.

>Destructive daruma karma cannon is a more offensive version of junk sleep., but is less effective strategy-wise.

>Mound of the bound creator boosts sandions burn damage by 1K to total 3000 and remedies the most pressing concern of non-destructive targeting removal

Overall the deck functions as a reliable anti-meta deck in the modern format and can win you some locals. Keep in mind, the biggest concern is non-destructive non-targeting removal, which is why i have included a playset of cosmic cyclone. Foolish burial, one for one and harpie's are all viable one-of's you can replace it with if your locals are not flooded with this kind of removal.

Red-Eyes by far is a terrible archetype to run pure, I have been wasting my time trying to get a pure Red-Eyes deck that works and I think i've stumbled along something that works. One of Red-Eyes largest downside is the massive amounts of level 6 and 7 monster you need if you want to keep a lot of fusion and XYZ monsters on the field. Another big downside is the 50/50 first hand casual Red-Eyes decks usually have and I believe I have remedied this issue with this deck.

Notes (differences from a casual Red-Eyes Deck):

1. Instead of worry about summoning anything lower than a level 6 monster from the hand I have outright removed every Red-Eyes card that below level 6, all of them (except the Black Stone of Legend, are useless and waste space)

2. All Fusion monster come straight from the deck or graveyard via Necro Fusion or Red-Eyes Fusion, any other method of Fusion is unviable with this high a level of monster.

3. Red-Eyes souls can be summoned if you get turn two from the hand which allows for powerful XYZ options in combination with a Fusion Monster.

General Turn Starters:

Red-Eyes Fusion > Meteor Black Comet Dragon (using a Red-Eyes Black Meteor Dragon) > Next turn using Black Meteor's effect

Red-Eyes Insight > Red-Eyes Fusions sending Black Meteor to graveyard

Dragon Shrine > Red-Eye BD. and BMD. to Graveyard

Set Necro Fusions > Various Card Effects to get a stash in graveyard

This deck is generally good at both turns but with my experience with it, its better off going first to get a better chance of Necro Fusion going through.

deck_excerpt: Disaster Dragons with some twisted (Fiendish) chains
deck_description:
Went undefeated at locals a few times and done well pretty much every other time.

Warior lady removes herself to keep totem dragon live

Double masked dragon into exploder dragon to (usually) force them to stop attacking or make them 1:1 with something at the end

Plague as the only tuner but being able to revive him and do it twice + keep him out of the grave for totem dragon.

Fiendish Chains deal with problems like Judgment Dragon, Archlord Kristya, until you can book of moon, lightning vortex, Brionac, etc, etc. Could clog the field but you will likely only have one out at a time and also have giant trunade to recycle them, or heavy storm to get rid of them later if needed. Also helps keep starlight road live if they heavy storm, etc. Ive found they dont really cause a problem though usually. Best to use on boss monsters (usually). Not ones that can easily be used as synchro material.

Chain Dissaperance in the side is really good against some decks like Dandywarrior. You can get rid of all of their quickdraws or dandylions and shut it down quickly.

Electric Virus is great against Lightsworn, Mirror Matches, and just a lot of decks since dragon synchros are so common in the format.

With Future Fusion I usually dump 2 Wyvern, 2 Darkness Metal, and Prime Material but obviously that depends on what else you already have.

deck_excerpt: Kashtira is a solid anti-meta strategy to counter all the graveyard dependent strategies running around this tier 1 "fire format."
deck_description:
This strategy's decklist is tailor made specifically for the March 2024 Masterduel meta. Kashtira is a solid anti-meta strategy to counter all the graveyard dependent strategies running around this tier 1 "fire format."

Kashtira is unbelievably powerful - but it has one main weakness... IT'S VASTLY INCONSISTENT! On top of that, Fenrir has finally been limited to 1 copy! This weakness is fixed with Small World, which serves as 3 extra cards of every single card in your Kashtira deck! Missing a starter?

Need a boardbreaker going second? Require a handtrap to to strengthen your gamestate? Search for it with Small World!

This is my personal deck that I reached Masters 1 this season since its now simultaneously consistent and strong!

Here are some examples of Small World lines:

Reveal Droll -> Gadarla -> Kashtira Unicorn

Reveal Ash Blossom -> Droll -> Kashtira Unicorn

Reveal Lava Golem -> Gadarla -> Kashtira Unicorn

Reveal Maxx "C" -> Kashtira Fenrir -> Planet Pathfinder

Reveal Kashtira Scareclaw -> Maxx "C" -> Planet Pathfinder

If you want a more in-depth guide to Kashtira, check out my article a couple months ago by clicking on this link!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: A bit more budget friendly Tear deck..... You can always throw in S:P and Triple Tactics cards to make it more viable :)
deck_description:
A bit more budget friendly Tear deck.....

You can always throw in S:P and Triple Tactics cards to make it more viable :)
Manga YGo GX Bastion MISAWA Yokai deck

13 card main deck engine means we can run every kind of non-engine imaginable. Unsure if I want 3X Fenrir, 3X Droplet or 3X Raigeki in the side deck, will test each.

Going first endboard will typically be Spheres + Handtraps. Sometimes you can make Black-Winged Assault Dragon instead. Situationally, Baronne can be the lone monster left on the field, but you need 2 card combos (And none of these cards can be Fadora) in hand to make that happen. Additionally, the Amblowhale + Princess board is achievable as well.

Trident Dragion can swing for 18k in a single Battle Phase. Trident effect pop field spell + bonus monster summoned off of Bident effect.

Deck goes crazy off of 12 1-card-starters. None of the Quick-Synch effects are HOTP

Prosperity OTK:

Baidora -> add Sangen Manor -> Manor add Zhongdora -> Zhongdora summon itself -> Enter Battle. Attack with Zhongdora -> Effect to Summon Fadora in Damage Step -> Attack with Baidora -> Effect to Quick Synch using Baidora and Zhongdora into Bident Dragon -> Effect of Bident to summon Baidora -> Attack with Bident -> Effect of Fadora in Damage Step to Summon Zhongdora -> Attack with Fadora -> Quick Synch using Fadora and Bident to make Trident -> Trident pop the Sangen Manor and one of the bonus Tenpais -> effect of Sangen Manor to double Trident's attack -> Swing for 18K (9K under Prosp)

 

Zhondora 1-card:

Normal Zhongdora -> enter Battle Phase. Attack with Zhongdora -> Effect during Damage Step to summon Baidora -> Baidora effect to add Sangen Kaimen -> Attack with Baidora -> Quick Synch into Bident -> Bident effect to summon Baidora -> Activate Sangen Kaimen in Battle to add and then summon Fadora -> Attack with Bident -> Effect of Fadora in Damage Step to Summon Zhongdora -> Attack with Fadora -> Quick Synch using Fadora and Bident to make Sangen Superdragon -> Swing for game, if lacking damage, activate Bident in Grave to reborn.

 

Sangen Kaimen 1-card

Sangen Kaimen, add Baidora-> Normal Baidora -> add Sangen Manor -> Manor add Zhongdora -> Zhongdora summon itself -> Enter Battle. Attack with Zhongdora -> Effect to Summon Fadora in Damage Step -> Attack with Baidora -> Effect to Quick Synch using Baidora and Zhongdora into Bident Dragon -> Effect of Bident to summon Baidora -> Attack with Bident -> Effect of Fadora in Damage Step to Summon Zhongdora -> Attack with Fadora -> Quick Synch using Fadora and Bident to make Trident -> Trident pop the Sangen Manor and one of the bonus Tenpais -> effect of Sangen Manor to double Trident's attack -> Swing for 18K (9K under Prosp)

 

 Brimming Sangen Manor 1-Card:

Sangen Manor -> Add Baidora -> Normal Baidora -> Add Sangen Kaimen -> Enter Battle Phase. Sangen Kaimen -> add then summon Zhongdora -> Attack with Zhongdora -> Effect to Summon Fadora in Damage Step -> Attack with Baidora -> Effect to Quick Synch using Baidora and Zhongdora into Bident Dragon -> Effect of Bident to summon Baidora -> Attack with Bident -> Effect of Fadora in Damage Step to Summon Zhongdora -> Attack with Fadora -> Quick Synch using Fadora and Bident to make Trident -> Trident pop the Sangen Manor and one of the bonus Tenpais -> effect of Sangen Manor to double Trident's attack -> Swing for 18K (9K under Prosp)

 

Gold Sarc adds 1 garnet to create another 1-card. Gold Sarc send Blaster, Blaster effect to add missing name in hand, or Baidora for best 1-card. Zhongdora line plays through Droll and Nibiru.

Relativamente pochi cambiamenti in questo terzo episodio, ma decisamente significativi! Ci liberiamo degli ultimi 1500 in attacco senza reali effetti, e aggiungiamo carte come Controllo della Mente, Cavalleria Samurai di Reptier, che possiamo searchare con Oviraptor, e un mostro da Extra Deck abbastanza evocabile come GranSolfaccordo Coolia! E ovviamente, quello che speriamo possa diventare il nostro Boss Monster, il Malvagio Terrorizzatore! 

Relatively few changes between the second and the third episode, but very significant ones! We got rid of the last 1500 ATK monsters with basically no effects, and we found awesome cards like Brain Control, Samurai Cavalry of Reptier, which we can search with Ovyraptor, and an Extra Deck monster that's actually kinda playable, like GranSolfachord Coolia! And what we hope can become our true Boss Monster, the Wicked Dreadroot!

deck_excerpt: A holy dragon appears on a beautiful starry night with a knight in a white robe on its back.
deck_description:
~Starry Knight~

 

 

Starry Knight is a semi-control Deck focusing on having Level 7 Dragons on the board or hand, enabling various disruptions supported by Light Fairies with various Hand, resource generating or Graveyard effects.

 

 

Starry Knight Rayel - The best “Starry Knight” Normal Summon tutoring a “Starry Knight” Spell/Trap from your Deck, in most cases fetching Starry Knight Balefire. Can revive another name by banishing itself from the Graveyard. 

Starry Knight Orbitael - Can Tribute itself to set a “Starry Knight” Spell/Trap directly from your Deck, in most cases fetching you endboard pieces like Starry Knight Blast. Can revive itself when a Light Dragon returns to hand.

Starry Knight Flamel - Extra name with a niche battle effect. Triggers Orbitael’s Graveyard effect

Starry Night, Starry Dragon - The Deck’s boss monster. On summon non once per turn destruction, and when battling it can Galaxy Eyes Photon Dragon a monster it battles, while also having protection against Dark attribute monsters.

Starry Knight Balefire - One of the best cards in the Deck. Tutoring your “Starry Knight” monsters or Light Dragons, having a niche effect to special said dragon if your opponent controls Dark monsters and your field is empty.

Starry Knight Ceremony - Unbricks your Fairies and tutors Dragon. On reaction to an opponent’s card effect you get to Special Summon Dragon from hand to destroy a card and make Starry Knight Blast live.

Starry Knight Blast - Free omni as long Dragon is on the board. Triggers Orbitael’s Graveyard effect.

Starry Knight Arrival - Another way to pull Dragon out of the hand. Triggers Orbitael’s Graveyard effect

 

 

~Melodious~

 

 

Melodious is a control Deck focusing on Fusion Summoning and setting a big variety of locks preventing the opponent from destroying their cards. Here we are abusing their Branded Fusion, Ostinato to generate great amounts of resources.

 

 

 

Ostinato - One of the best Branded Fusion like cards in game, being non once per turn allows you to use it to bait Ash. This card is your soul and blood as it starts all your plays.

 

Melodious Concerto - Polymerization with the addition of being able to utilize scales. Draws 1 when a Fusion is sent to the GY.

 

Refrain the Melodious Songstress - The best “Melodious” Normal Summon tutoring a “Melodious” monster, in this case Couplet. Returns to the Pendulum zone when a “Melodious” Fusion is summoned.

 

Couplet the Melodious Songstress - When added she Special Summons a “Melodious” from your hand or Graveyard. Returns to the Pendulum zone when a “Melodious” Fusion is summoned. Tutors “Melodious” Spell/Traps while in the Pendulum Zone.

 

Bacha the Melodious Maestra - Emergency Teleports a “Melodious on Special Summon. Reborns a “Melodious” when sent to the Graveyard. Important combo piece.

 

(Optional) Schuberta the Melodious Maestra - D.D. Crow on legs.

 

(Optional) Flowering Etoile the Melodious Grand Choir - S:P Little Knight for Melodious.

 

 

~Engines & Options~

 

 

Traptrix - 1x Traptrix Rafflesia, 1x Gravediggers Trap Hole: Endboard option to stop hand/Graveyard effects.

 

Heatsoul - 1x Mecha Phantom Beast Dracossack, 1x Decode Talker Heatsoul, 1x G Golem Crystal Heart, 2x Link Spider: Helps you draw into your Starry Knight cards.

 

Armored XYZ - 1x Armored XYZ, 1x Full-Armored XYZ, 1x XYZ Armor Fortress, 1x Full Armored Dark Knight Lancer, 1x Starring Knight: Big Beater with both Spell and Trap operating as disruption.

 

Photon - 1x Photon Sanctuary, 1x Galaxy Photon Dragon, 1x Eternal Galaxy, 1x Bujinki Ahashima, 1x Number 90: Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord, 1x Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy: Endboard option to stop Monsters or Spells on top of backrow removal.

 

Pendulum Dragons - 1x Odd-Eyes Absolute Dragon, 1x Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon: An option over the Heatsoul line, making a negate with spin on summon.

 

 

~Combo Theory~

 

 

All your combos stem from Ostinato with Starry Knight coming in once your scales are fully set-up:

 

Base combo: Ostinato summon Bacha the Melodious Maestra by sending both Couplet and Refrain the Melodious Songstresses > Bacha summons a copy of Refrain from your Deck > Refrain adds Couplet > Couplet effect upon being added summon back the Couplet in your Graveyard > Couplet Scale effect add Melodious Concerto > Concerto fuse Scale Couplet and a Refrain for Bacha > both Fusion materials become Scales > make Dracossack (Tokens into 2x Link Spiders > both Spiders into G Golem Crystal Heart > Heart reborns a copy of Spider > Spider and Heart into Heatsoul) or Odd-Eyes Absolute Dragon. This last part will always result in a body being brought back by Bacha and Concerto drawing 1. Before Pendulum Summoning always make sure to Link away your Melodious to generate more resources.
WIP Psychic Synchro

Reached master rank with this deck farily quickly. Only took one day to make it through diamond as seemingly everyone surrenders on the first turn in that rank.

Typical endboard is alba zoa and guilding quim with fleurdelis in hand with an extra negate. Fallen of albaz is in grave and can brought to field off a monster leaving extra deck. Most people dont know that quim is a dogmatika and protected by alba zoa.

The bystial is included to help build chaos angel or pull an albaz from the grave.

An underated card to get around a lot of the meta is to make an albion as it can't be targeted my anything including fusions.

Ash and droll will pretty much stop anything if you are forced to go second.

Hope this deck helps anyone trying to get creative and beat the current meta.

deck_excerpt: "Soulcharge" every turn all your Horus monsters with this anti-meta build! AWAKEN MY MASTERS!
deck_description:
With Phantom Nightmare, Horus receives its second wave of support, allowing the deck to be actually played pure! As a "pure" deck, Horus turbos out a ton of beatsticks with high ATK and that are notoriously hard to remove without the opponent being severely punished. 
 
The deck is also very compatible with crippling floodgates like Skill Drain and Summon Limit, both cards that obliterate current meta strategies. This deck also shrugs off handtraps that most duelists crowd their maindecks with, like Impermanence, Effect Veiler, Ghost Belle, Nibiru and Droll (the only exception is Ash Blossom which hurts Nadir Servant and Imsety). 
 
If you've been looking for a proper anti-meta deck that can reliably facedown "fire format" decks, or you're simply looking for something else to play other than Snake-Eyes/Diabellstar/Fire King you may have found the correct deck! 
 
Shoutout to Steve V.'s Light and Darkness Horus deck profile (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6EweR3awMug) for inspiring me to create this Horus deck. Be sure to check out their video!
 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 

ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING 

 

"Pure" Horus is an anti-meta beatdown stun deck, designed to counter all the combo heavy midrange decks rampant during this "fire format." Combining both archetypes, these strategies create a powerful beatdown playstyle with easy-to-summon hard-to-kill monsters! 

 

The HORUS cards are maxxed out for this deck and is composed of 16 cards - 3 Imsety, 1 Hapi, 1 Duamutef, 1 Qebehsenuef, 3 Walls of the Imperial Tomb, 3 Canopic Protector and 3 King's Sarcophagus. 1 Terraforming searches Walls of the Imperial Tomb, making it another starter. 

 

This DOGMATIKA package is normally what you'd see in stun decks, and it is adopted for this strategy. 3 Nadir Servant, 2 Ecclesia, and 2 Dogmatika Punishment along with it's usual Extra Deck ammunition. 

 

7 FLOODGATES are maindecked, since they cripple most strategies that are rampant this format, while hardly affecting your Horus cards. These floodgates can be easily exchanged for boardbreakers when forced to go second by your opponent. 

 

The rest of the deck are STAPLE cards. This strategy opts to go for boardbreakers since it cannot fit critical mass of handtraps to stop the extremely resilient combo decks running around this format. 3 Talents are used since it's extremely good this format with all the monster effects being activated. 3 Fenrir and 3 Lava Golem are used to break boards. 1 Mudora and 1 Keldo are used since this deck discards a lot, and these graveyard shufflers hardcounter the graveyard dependent fire decks using Promethean Princess, Linkriboh and level 1 Snake-Eyes cards. 1 Called By the Grave is used to counter the multitude of handtraps running around this format. 

 

 

42 cards are used to ensure this strategy is as consistent and compact as possible while reducing the chance of drawing into bricks/garnets.

 

COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN 

 

Anti-Meta Horus' gameplan is to overwhelm your opponent with beefy difficult-to-remove beatsticks while floodgating/interrupting/negating your opponent's plays. There is no mainline "combo" to this deck - the gameplay is mostly dependent on situational decisions done by the pilot. 

 

First, you break your opponent's board, which is done by using any of the 12 boardbreakers in the deck. Also, Horus cards inherently break boards in-engine, whether its through the battlephase with King's Sarcophagus when attacking with any Horus monster. Nadir Servant also can use the variety of Extra Deck monster ammunition for a toolbox of removal effects, like N'tss destruction and Malong's bounce. 

 

Second, you establish your board and gamestate. The Horus cards fill the graveyard, set Canopic Protector for limitless summons, and maybe set up negates in the form of Hope Harbinger or Photon Lord (now affordable in the TCG thanks to Battles of Legend: Chapter 1!)

 

If Canopic Protector is set up on your field, you can use all your Horus monsters to make Rank 8 plays or Link plays with I:P + S:P to bring all your Horus monsters in the GY. Canopic Protector will summon them all from the GY anyways when your opponent activates any monster effect! 

 

From that set-up, you should be able to play a decent and powerful game of Yugioh with Anti-Meta Horus. Horus cards are surprisingly and ridiculously hard to remove easily due to their effects triggering whenever a card on the field is removed by card effect! Imsety sends a card to the GY, Qebehsenuef protects from targeting, Hapi recovers 2 from Banishment/GY, and Duamutef draws up to 5 cards! King's Sarcophagus protects Horus monsters from destruction unless they are targeted, so cards like Mirrorjade, Raigeki and Lightning Storm don't do much. Finally, Canopic Protector basically is "soul charge" for Horus, summoning Horus monsters everytime your opponent does anything! 

 

This deck is an anti-meta deck designed to counter the handtrap-heavy meta that is rampant in the TCG right now - and both Dogmatika and Horus strategies shrug off almost every handtrap thown at them. Impermanence, Effect Veiler, Ghost Belle, Nibiru and Droll all get easily dealt with if you sequence your cards right. The exception to this is the ever present Ash Blossom, which if well-timed may stop certain crucial plays. 

 

 

GENERAL TIPS

  • This strategy maindecks 12 boardbreaking cards (3 Lava Golem, 3 Kashtira Fenrir, 3 Talents, 3 Nadir Servant). That number can be brought up to 19 by siding out all the floodgates in the deck for 3 Evenly Matched, 3 Thrust, and 1 Cosmic Cyclone. This will almost certainly guarantee you to break your opponent's board so you can set up your Horus cards during the crackback. 
  • Canopic Protector is Horus' most powerful card, since it can summon all the Horus monsters from the GY as this deck's "soul charge!" Try to get this incredible card set up! 
  •  When your Horus monster's effects trigger, try to leave Imsety/Qebehsenuef as last in the chain to chainblock Hapi/Duamutuf so your opponent cannot Ash Blossom or Ghost Belle their effects!
  • If you have a floodgate set up along with Canopic Protector with a packed GY, you're usually going to win the game due to your endless summons while your opponent cannot do much. 
  • Activate "The Zombie Vampire's" effect to set up your GY with Horus monsters while giving you an S:P Little Knight with a double banish!
     
    Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 

CONCLUDING REMARKS

 
I haven't created a proper TCG guide to a deck in a while since there is nothing really viable this format because those pesky fire decks really make this format one-dimensional and frankly, boring due to the lack of variety. That is why I was inspired to cook this spicy deck anti-meta deck, Horus Dogmatika, which is a feeble attempt to hardcounter those flaming hot tyrants that dominate the metagame! This deck might not win every single game - but hey, it's not Snake-Eyes Fire King! 
 
Someone will have to stand up to the endless combos, 20+ action turns and 15+ handtrap decks, and I sincerely think that "pure" Horus is the anti-meta deck capable od such a challenge to the "Fire Format!" 
 
GLHF duelists!

deck_excerpt: As a wise man once said "Im-a guess Im-a go fishing".
deck_description: Most likely to get slapped by fish.

Winged Kuriboh LV6 makes E - Emergency Call and Infernal Wingman's search much more powerful; Favorite Contact is also less of a dead draw. Koga is also more viable now that almost half of our HEROs are Light attribute (WK LV6 counts!). Chaos Angel instead of Masked HERO Acid because of WK LV6 and Malicious both being, well, LV6; this would make for some interesting Plan Bs if you can get either out with a Vyon or Shadow Mist that has been hand-trapped and you dont want to go into Little Knight for whatever reason. Either Vyon or Shadow Mist + WK LV6 would summon Chaos Angel with both passive protections added. I cut Acid because of our other methods available to use for popping backrow and our side deck having more to deal with Spells/Traps.

If you want to get to that golden 40 card list then consider cutting: 1 Triple Tactics Talent, 1 E - Call, 1 Rivalry, and 1 WK LV6. However, HERO doesn't mind having up to ~45 cards, it adds balance between not drawing our bricks, and we search almost anything else. 

Don't cut Blast from the extra deck as it provides protection from Imperm/Veiler for Stratos, as well as helps with backrow in a pinch.

Koga is the only one I'd replace if you want the link 3 Xtra Hero or an extra Cross Crusader/Wonder Driver/Dark Law/DPE; but I don't think the protection for our light HEROs via Mask Change is worth giving up. 

Book of Eclipse and/or Crossout Designator+Droll are cards I'd like to fit in the deck somewhere, but testing is recquired to see what to cut from the maindeck.

deck_description: Duelist Cup replays - https://youtu.be/PsVlN_IKRkM
darkness rules
They're so gay
Fuck you Spork

Basically the goal is to draw a slifer trap or trap trick to get the slifer trap, and either branded fusion or foolish burial to get slifer in the grave yard, and then deplete your hand of as many non hand traps as possible and pass to the opponent. Then you will have a 6 card hand with slifer on the field and feel very powerful and can get him back on the turn after and go for the kill.

Purpose of certain cards:

Goal: getting slifer trap

-3 trap tricks, so you have 6 total cards in the deck that can get you Slifer reving from the graveyard plus drawing till you reach 6 cards in hand. You will basically be just as likely as puling one of these cards as getting an ash or maxx c when you have 3 of each, so the consistancy is pretty good for getting a slifer trap.
-I run 3 of Albion the shrouded dragon because it is a cheap draw 1 card, and it sends a card to the graveyard, thus increasing the chances of drawing a slifer trap/trap trix or a path to branded fusion.
-magical mallet is there just for extra chances to pull the card you need, you can adjust it as necasary

Goal: getting slifer in the graveyard

-branded fusion, this is the heart of the slifer deck, as it lets you fusion into brigrand glory dragon, which lets you send slifer to the grave yard. As a bonus, brigrand protects all your monsters from being targeted with monster effects, so it is an added protection to your slifer.

-foolish burial, basically if you draw this card you don't need branded fusion for slifer and can essentially do a normal or full branded despia combo bc slifer is already in the graveyard.

Goal getting branded fusion:

-springans kitt if normal or special summoned, lets you add branded fusion to your hand and return another card from your hand to the deck.

-albur the jester of despia lets you search branded fusion and add it to your hand

-predaplant verte anaconda, if you have neither of the above than all you have to do is get 2 monsters on the field, then you can link summon verte and use it to get branded fusions ability


Extenders:

-Branded in red: is really good if you already get to branded fusion and have a slifer trap related card in hand, it essentially allows you, after you get slifer in the grave and brigrand on the field, to extend into getting another fusion monster on the field, I often do iceblade.

-blazing cartesia, is nice because if you use Albion the shrouded dragon to send albaz to the GY or you use incredible ecclesia to get albaz on the field she is a special summon. You can use her to get into a link 2 verte, if you dont have a card that searches it, or she can extend you into an extra fusion summon.

-branded opening is nice in the GY, for protection from your fusion monsters from getting destroyed.

If you dont want to build a whole branded deck and just want to play slifer, the only extra deck UR monster you need is predaplant verte for consistancy. If you want to run a weak branded, albian the branded dragon or lubellion the searching dragon, plus ice jade is all you really need.

For the main deck the only UR you need is branded fusion and the 3 slifer trap cards for consistancy, and 3 slifer. having all 3 slifer traps makes a huge difference for consistancy and fun.

right now in master duel branded fusion is limited to 1, and jester is limited to 2,

If you dont have alot of these UR or SR cards, feel free to use generic card drawers like magical mallet, reloaded, or others that you have to draw more cards, or just fill it with staples/generic good cards. You can also replace alot of the non jester, springan kitt, albaz, and albion, branded or depsia cards with Egyptian God themed cards.
Egyptian God themed cards are only good if you draw slifer in your hand, which is hard because slifer cannot be searched. But if you draw slifer and one of the egyptian God themed cards, it helps you to get tributes to normal/tribute summon slifer. But this is the main reason branded is good, because you will basically get slifer every other game, whereas without branded its super rare to get him because foolish burial is limited to 1 and slifer cant be searched.

deck_excerpt: Mekk-Knights made specifically for March 2024 Duelist Cup! Time to "MEKK" IT HAPPEN!!!
deck_description:
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

*Columns exist* Yes... It's MEKKIN TIME!!!!!


No in-depth explanation for this decklist, Mekk-Knights are fairly straight forward and already figured out. :)

Clear your opponent's board to create a simplified gamestate with this deck's many boardbreakers, then methodically force a grind game with Mekk-Knight's swarm, beatdown and resource gathering ability. This is mainly done with the 12 searchers this deck has access to, that being Mekk-Knight Purple Nightfall, Blue-Sky, Orcust Girsu, and World Legacy's Memory.

Hard-to-out extra deck bosses are usually the win condition in this deck, like a I:P Masquereena boosted Avramax, an untargetable/undestroyable Mekk-Knight Spectrum Supreme or the column-dependent battle phase champion Mekk-Knight Morning Star.


In a simplified gamestate vacuum, Mekk-Knight Avramax is nigh-unkillable and often is a "checkmate" on your opponent. Zeus can also be used comfortably in this deck, enabled by easy access to Mekk-Knight Orcust Girsu -> Galatea -> Dingirsu.

GLHF Duelists!
Yet another Utopia deck

The Majespecter archetype introduces a refreshing and unique approach to Yu-Gi-Oh! gameplay, blending adorable creature designs with powerful spell and trap support. With the addition of new support cards, the Majespecter deck has seen a significant power boost, making it a formidable contender even in competitive play, allowing for more strategic plays and enhanced consistency. "The inclusion of search cards like "Necrovalley" and "Village of the Spellcasters" is a valuable addition to the Majespecter arsenal."

This synergy between the Majespecter archetype and support cards adds a layer of versatility to the deck, enabling duelists to adapt to various matchups and strategies (and a Lot of HandTraps! :D)

Hello everyone i recenly started playing sharks and i made decklist which i think is pretty good and fun.As from what i have seen people either play sharks with full armored xyz cards or nash knight.I mixed both of them since i really like both and i feel like its less bricky.This deck list runs a lot of extenders so there is gonna be less times where Ash is gonna end ur turn.This decklist either ends on Silent Honor Dark with Honor arc in gy,Toad and Kragen or Full Armored Crystalzero Lancer with Full-armored Xyz set on field so you can summon next turn Armored Lancer and suck one monster with gy effect,Toad and Kragen.Combos are Bahamut into Toad then Xyz Armor Fortress detach 2 to search spell and trap go into Crystalzero,go into Kragen if you have extenders if not then set full-armored xyz and use next turn as i have said earlier.Second board is Bahamut into Toad then use some extenders into N.A.S.H knight effect detach 2 use Honor Arc as material, summon that into CXyz Knight,Knight effect to detach Arc summon into Honor Dark and go into Kragen if possible.This second board is better if go second since you can just suck monster on your turn with Honor Dark.We got Dweller and Zeus as our last cards in Extra,Dweller if op plays gy heavy deck and Zeus is pretty good since you have few monsters that are battle immune and right-hand shark can give protection to any monster so its not that hard to pull Zeus.This deck strugles going second if op have lot of negs but ur kind of screwed going second anyway.Thats it about this deck hope someone likes it and if anyone got any questions feel free to ask.

Back at it again with another test, this time with the testing of no bonfires, and more Kashtira cards to get the engine going as with v1, Fenrir was the only searcher. This time we hope to take advantage of the field spell and trap card. While we may lose consistency with no bonfires for Priestess search, Prosperity can suppliment as necessary. More focused on board presence vs grind game.

If you want a grindier deck, swap the pots for consistency cards such as Bonfire and an additional copy of Kastiratheosis.

Flex spots are Nibiru, Called By the Grave, one copy of Kashtira Riseheart, and at least two copies of Pot of Prosperity. The main objective is to counter play the opponents counter play, as the format is heavy on searching, graveyard abuse, and back row counter play. Main signs to look out for is the obvous Fire King/ Snake Eye grave loops/ search loops, Summon Limits and the like.

Lastly Agnimal is included because its a Bonfire target, that specials itself on search, has level modulation to help summon Baronne **IF NECCESARY** and you dont have ot waste a hand-trap normal.

deck_name: Second Wind: A Return to Yugioh
deck_excerpt: An intermediate, short-range deck that rewards practice with a strategy that breaks your opponent's flow or wipes the field clean!
deck_description:
Although this deck's price and initial ratio set-up is pre-handled and tested, I recommend picking up this deck if you already understand a couple of the fundamentals of the game as this deck's obscure combos and rare mechanics can be rough for completely new players. If you're brave enough or have experienced friends you can rely on, don't let me scare you from having a great time (3/5 difficulty)! 

With that in mind, let's get started on the deck's strategies!

First, the way this deck wants to win comes in two separate flavors: Amano-Iwato is a barrier that restricts monster effects; and the two aces, Shinobaron Peacock and Shinobaroness Peacock, can sweep up any remaining board presence your opponent can have when they are uninterrupted. The ritual Ace monsters are easy to understand, so the discussion will mainly revolve around playing with Amano-Iwato. Here are some sample combos to get each of them set-up!

Aratama + Stars Align Above the Shrine: Use Aratama's effect to add Sakitama, use the effect of Sakitama to summon itself by revealing it, use the field spell "Stars Align Above the Shrine" to tribute Sakitama on the field to Ritual Summon "Shinobaroness Shade Peacock" or "Shinobaron Shade Peacock." Getting to these smaller ritual monsters helps you find ways to reach either win condition.

Shinobaron Shade Peacock: It's effect to tribute itself to get both a ritual spell and a ritual monster in hand is incredibly powerful. In most cases, you can use it to grab both "Shinobaroness Shade Peacock" and "Shinobird Calling", then use Shinobird Calling to ritual summon "Shinobaroness Shade Peacock" by banishing the "Shinobaron Shade Peacock" you used to find them. If you need to start an offense however, you can easily reach into a "Shinobaron Peacock" or a "Shinobaroness Peacock" to threaten your opponent's resources.

IMPORTANT: "Stars Align Across the Milky Way" can be accessed by having "Stars Align Above the Shrine" on the field when you leave a ritual monster face-up at the End Phase. This occurs because they are spirit monsters and return to the hand at the End Phase. It is also important because it is the more consistent way to reach Amano-Iwato with its secondary effect in the Graveyard. By banishing that trap card, you can ritual summon a monster from your hand (which needs to be Shinobaron Peacock or Shinobaroness Peacock for maximum impact), resolve its effects to return cards to the deck then Special Summon a Level 4 or lower Spirit Monster by dodging the conventional means applied to them. If your opponent often leads their combo with monsters, go for "Shinobaron Peacock" and try to set up with Amano-Iwato in the hand for a Special Summon! You can do this more easily by using "Shinobaroness Shade Peacock" to add "Shinobird Power Spot" to your hand, activating it, and having it's effect occur alongside your field spell at the End Phase.

But sometimes you can get lucky, and Amano-Iwato can start in your hand with the Yata Mirror equip spell. This can be deadly enough for plenty of decks if you are going first. If you have Amano-Iwato in hand and "Sakitama" + "Stars Align Above the Shrine," you can always try to cheese its staying power by ritual summoning into "Shinobaroness Shade Peacock" to get the mirror, then use Sakitama to add it itself to your hand, then summon out Amano-Iwato with its other effect.

Once you're proficient in this deck's combos, you may find yourself trying to finish the game with as little wiggle-room for your opponent. You can use "Yata-Garasu" to lock your opponent from making a comeback once you clean their field using either Ace Ritual monster(s).

How does the Extra Deck Work?: Sometimes your opponent has ways that can turn your unlucky hand upside down with an interruption. Many of the cards here (Abyss Dweller, Giant Hand, etc.) offer a field presence to hopefully survive until you can attempt another game-winning move. Many will know what "Divine Arsenal AA-Zeus Sky Thunder" does, but just in case- it offers another way to clear the board if you can successfully battle (and not destroy) your XYZ monsters. Every "Knightmare" card in the Extra Deck offers a new form of removal at the cost of effect monsters on your field and a card in your hand. Link Spider? Your combo will sometimes naturally make cute tokens to protect your lifepoints or can used as tributes for the ritual monsters in your hand. By link summoning "Link Spider" with one of the tokens, you will be one requirement closer to a "Knightmare" when you need it.

Elder Entity N'tss does not actually accompolish anything in the Deck on its own. But there are a few strategies that attempt to send your Extra Deck cards to the GY - and this can be a surprising punish.

The Side Deck?: These cards chosen naturally boost the initial given strategy in their own unique ways while being powerful staple cards that can be splashed or explored in other archetypes. It serves more as a preview of ways you could adjust the deck or lean into other exciting strategies instead. "Dogmatika" can be a ritual archetype to consider when looking to give your ritual summons a more diverse impact (They will also utilize the N'tss in the Extra Deck a lot more efficiently too!). Harpies often boost Wind attribute strategies that stuck to the original concept of wind monsters having benefits for returning to your hand to roost. And lastly, explosive cards such as "Evenly Matched" and "Gameciel, the Sea Turtle Kaiju" are obscure methods of removing problem cards from your opponent's field in ways that are hard to block without utilizing a ton of their prepared resources and makes your Going Second turns with your Ritual Monsters even more potent!

This deck is built to carry plenty of splashable cards that make building other decks easier, alongside being cheaper than any given meta, and flexible enough to grow alongside an attentive player. Whether a new player, returning from an ancient memory of the game, or a coming back after a monthly break, I think you'll find this deck to be the perfect match navigating through the modern era of Yugioh.

Meklord. Ra. Prediction Princess. Earthbound. Horus.

Deck Archetype - Control   Deck Difficulty - Medium

 

Deck Evaluation

Dark Magician has received quite a lot of dedicated support, making it have a flexible playstyle
Chaos monsters have innate synergy with the Dark Magician archetype
Has a surprising amount of options for the Extra Deck, with a focus on using Level 6 and Level 7 monsters
 
Core Combos and Interactions;
 
 
Illusion of Chaos Engine
- Illusion of Chaos and Magicians' Souls make for a very consistent combo that provides quite an consistent combo for card advantage. The Ritual Monster searches out the latter Effect Monster, then after being added on the hand, can discard Illusion of Chaos to Special Summon Dark Magician straight from the Deck.
 
Dark Magician Early Summon
- This is your other main combo to get Dark Magician out onto the field as soon as possible. Use Magicians' Souls to send a Dark Magician to the GY and activate Eternal Soul to Special Summon it onto the field.
 

Dark Magician the Dragon Knight

- Another Dragon Fusion monster, this time summoning Dark Magician the Dragon Knight. With another Spellcaster monster to send from the field or hand to the, you can Special Summon Timaeus the United Dragon and Fusion Summon Dark Magician the Dragon Knight. It's a powerful boss monster that protects your Spells and Traps from being targeted and destroyed by card effects..

The White Stone of Ancients

You can banish a Spell/Trap if the opponent controls one. Reveal a copy of Blue-Eyes White Dragon from the hand to Special Summon Blue-Eyes Alternative White Dragon from the hand. If the opponent has a monster on the field, activate Blue-Eyes Alternative White Dragon to destroy a monster the opponent controls. 
 At the End Phase, the effect of The White Stone of Ancients will trigger, and Special Summon Blue-Eyes Jet Dragon from the Deck.

deck_excerpt: Diabellstar Snake-Eye Fire King  / Merida WCQ Regional 2nd Place
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Alastair Lopez Gonzalez

Tournament: Merida WCQ Regional – March 10th 2024

Placement: 2nd Place

Despite this archetype having some dead weight cards I actually find it to be quite good, it's consistent and very flexible. It's also got incredible control capabilities and can start growing out of hand with power over time thanks to its leveling system. Dealing with it isn't a cakewalk either, Shining Sarcophagus is indestructible to monster effects and the swordsman can negate anything that targets it as well!

And despite being control oriented it even has a consistent way to win! When the time is right you can use the sarcophagus's search effect to grab gandora, gandora will summon itself and bomb everything (except shining sarcophagus) and summon another monster from your deck and level it up based on how many cards were destroyed! Destroy enough cards and summon swordsman or magician and it'll be an otk!

Deck Archetype - Aggro   Deck Difficulty - Medium

 

Core Combos and Interactions;
 
 
Red-Eyes Early Summon
- These are the fastest ways to get a Red-Eyes Black Dragon onto the field. You can use a Black Dragon's Chick if you have Red-Eyes Black Dragon in your hand, or use The Black Stone of Legend if all your Red-Eyes Black Dragons are in your deck.
 
Red-Eyes Darknes Dragon
- Summoning Red-Eyes Darkness Dragon is exactly like summoning Red-Eyes Black Dragon early, just with an additional step of tributing your Red-Eyes Black Dragon to summon Red-Eyes Darkness Dragon. Summoning Red-Eyes Darkness Dragon this way gives you an additional effect of adding two more Dragon Monsters to your GY, giving it an additional 600 ATK on top of its 2400 ATK. This will only increase given the number of Dragon Monsters you have in your GY.
 
Meteor Black Comet Dragon
- A very simple way to Fusion Summon Meteor Black Comet Dragon. All you need to do is use Red-Eyes Fusion during your main phase and pick the necessary monsters to fuse and you can Special Summon it to the field. As soon as you Special Summon Meteor Black Comet Dragon, you can activate its effect to send a Red-Eyes monster to the GY and directly deal damage to your opponent equal to half the original ATK of the selected Red-Eyes monster.
 
Archfeind Black Skull Dragon
- A very simple way to Fusion Summon Archfiend Black Skull Dragon. All you need to do is use Red-Eyes Fusion during your main phase and pick the necessary monsters to fuse and you can Special Summon it to the field. Archfiend Black Skull Dragon has a unique effect that whenever damage calculation is performed involving this monster, at the end of the Battle Phase, you can select one Red-Eyes monster in your GY and inflict damage directly to your opponent equal to the chosen monster's original ATK before shuffling the card from your GY back to your deck.
 
Red-Eyes Flare Metal Dragon
- A great monster to have on the field. Using a Red-Eyes Black Dragon and Red-Eyes Black Flare Dragon as material, you can summon it onto the field. While Red-Eyes Flare Metal Dragon is on the field, it'll deal 500 damage directly to your opponent each time they activate a card or effect after it resolves.
 
Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon
- Another fairly easy summon. You can actually replace Red-Eyes Baby Dragon with any face-up Dragon Monster you have on the field. Red-Eyes Baby Dragons may be the best bet as you'll need to banish the chosen face-up Dragon Monster to successfuly summon the Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon. Once per turn during your Main Phase, you can use its effect to Special Summon 1 Dragon Monster from either your hand or GY to the field.

bong

Generaly

This Deck is made to do Cubic stuff , distribute cubic counters , stall , negate effects , negate attacks and slap with big monsters without using much of other engines because it ruins the cubic experience , you may as well play a better archetype if youd rather play cubics just for the Duza the Meteor Cubic Vessel and Unification of the Cubic Lords interaction for extra deck plays, so this deck here is made to help you suffer as less as possible with unplayable hands and getting your plays ruined by a single Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring.

Goals

Fragile to interaction deck that can get out resourced by stronger decks , your goal is to survive untill  you can stabilize for a turn to slap a big monster like Crimson Nova the Dark Cubic Lord or Topologic Zeroboros  on a near empty field, Topologic Zeroboros can clean the field itself if enemy doesnt have interaction.

Cards Used

Duza the Meteor Cubic Vessel is your starter generaly helping send Unification of the Cubic Lords to the graveyard to either proceed with link plays , or stall for time by searching an indestructible cubic on its removal from the field. Unification of the Cubic Lords can also be used to search Indiora Doom Volt the Cubic Emperor or Buster Gundil the Cubic Behemoth as a way to search to your hand specific cubic cards on their destruction, like Cubic Mandala.

Crimson Nova the Dark Cubic Lord is the big boss , untargetable by most monster effects can potentially attack twice per turn and has effect damage, and only for the small price of revealing 3 cubic cards from your hand you can special summon it. The usuall way si to get lucky with opening hand , or by discarding Cubic Karma to search for different cubic monsters to fullfill the condition.

Vijam the Cubic Seed is our main stall tool , unsuspecting enemies will attack it while its set and get surprised with a cubic counter on their monster.

deck_excerpt: Branded Opening to 1? Believe it or not, 60 card Branded is still as powerful and consistent as it is before!
deck_description:
Branded Fusion to 1, Saronir to 1, and now Branded Opening to 1? WHY DOES MASTERDUEL HATE ALBAZ AND FRIENDS?

Nah... I'd STILL win. Believe it or not, 60 card Branded is still as powerful and consistent as it is before! Able to play through commonly used turn-stopping cards like Dimension Shifter, Maxx "C," Nibiru, and Droll Branded is a top pick for Masterduel's meta right now! This deck has so much plays that even an Ash Blossom on Branded Fusion can be shrugged off!

Konami's favourite lore deck (and my personal favourite!) is able to contest the tier 1 fire decks running rampant around ladder right now with it's incredible grindgame, powerful beatsticks, and non-targeting/destroying removal!

If you're looking for the perfect deck to pilot that can slice through those annoying omni-negate decks or those pesky fire decks, while strong and consistent enough to create it's own powerful boards, Branded Fusion is the deck for you!

Chances are if you're reading this, you've been piloting Branded for a couple years now (wow time flies fast) and you don't need a combo guide for the deck. However, if you wanna read up an article I made, feel free to check out my guide!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

test

I tried to make a competitive deck out of morphtronic with the main strategies is to roll dices and get morph to make synchros.

foolish burial goods and clockwork night will help getting access to your monsters (depending of the situation, scannen, gadget gamer and celfon can be starters, smarfon to extend).

Don't be afraid to use scannen, this decklist can lack to make big synchros and that levek 6 help a lot. Go add the gadget box with it and go for the power tool dragon.

If you have another morphtronic in your hand after making the power tool, you can go grab repair unit from your deck by the power tool effect, then special summon the last morph in your hand (if it is smartfon, you can banish scannen from GY instead).depending of the morphtronic you had (level 3 or 1 tuner) you can either make crystal wing or baronne before the 5th summon and protect you from most handtraps without having to normal summon !

formula synchron can be a really good in you endboard if coupled with crystal wing or naturia beast, it can make baronne to switch to an omni negate or go for the black rose dragon and clean the board.

I usually end up with the power tool braver dragon equipped with life stream (+ earfon sometimes) making an effect veiler/removal if combined with earfon for the cost. Having only one equip spell mean that if it use its effect, it has no protection, so I put Life Stream dragon to special summon it after using the braver effect. This let me wih a powerful body and  a protect on it.

I wanted to add handtraps so the morphronic part is restrictive but having 13 sumonable names is already great and can easely lead to extends and combo (if the dice is with you)

 

Enjoy it :)

deck_excerpt: Combining P.U.N.K and Gold pride does wonders
deck_description: Pretty powerfull MD deck that lets me win against many Meta decks, depending on how well the opponent plays (perfect snake-eyes is pretty hard to counter for any deck anyways) though i managed to win against any non-meta deck, labrynth and Kashtira so far.

This deck aims to summon the legendary exodia incarnate after sending most of the peices to the graveyard. This creates a 5000 attack monster that is completely unnafected by card effects, and this becomes even more dangerous with continuous effects like OBLITERATE!!!, summon limit, and imperial iron wall, all of which can be protected by lord of the heavenly prison, who can be overlayed with other exodia monsters to make powerful rank 10 XYZ monsters.

deck_excerpt: Pisa WCQ Regional 2nd place - Dalla Valle Matteo
deck_description:
Pisa WCQ Regional

2nd place - Dalla Valle Matteo

The main line with this deck is to have a summonable Alpha Thuban + Bright Knight/Nova/Emergency. 

  1. Summon Thuban -> search Ophiel
  2. Summon Bright Knight -> search Fafnir
  3. Fafnir -> search Ursarctic Drytron
  4. Ursarctic -> banish Fafnir/Dipper -> summon Flagship
  5. Link Thuban into Linkuriboh -> trigger Flagship -> search Gamma Eltanin
  6. Overlap Flagship + Knight into Dracossack -> Dracossack detach for 2 tokens
  7. Link 1 token for Link Spider under Linkuriboh -> Linkuriboh + Spider into G Golem
  8. G Golem summons Spider -> Heatsoul
  9. Other token + Dracossack -> Masquerena (or leave them for an Apollousa later)
  10. Summon Eltanin by banishing Ursarctic Drytron for replacement -> Summon Thuban
  11. Overlay Eltanin + Thuban for Mu Beta -> dump Zeta Aldhibah
  12. Aldhibah tribute Ophiel -> search Meteonis 
  13. Meteonis summon Ophiel by detaching 1 from Mu Beta
  14. Ophiel search Phul 1
  15. Ophiel summons Phul 1 by tributing itself
  16. Phul 1 summons Phul 2 from deck by tributing itself

From here you can do whatever. Phul is for summoning Bethor and getting 1-3 pops. Ideally you have a way to dump Draconids before Phul 2 so you can add it back with Phul and get the level gain (e.g. if you draw Aldhibah, dump Draconids with Mu Beta instead). 

Is this deck good? Ehhhhhhhhhh

Handtrap choices are dealer's choice. I like Phantazmay as another lv7 but it can conflict with the Drytron summon restrictions.
Teste

deck_excerpt: Pisa WCQ Regional  3rd place - Rossi Flaminio
deck_description:
Pisa WCQ Regional 

3rd place - Rossi Flaminio

True Draco is a less popular deck that can still be enjoyable to play and win with. While it may not be a top-tier deck, it can still perform well in events. Since the ban of Master Peace, the deck has relied more on floodgates, such as Skill Drain and Boarder. I have been testing and playing this deck at various events, facing opponents with different decks, and has had mostly even or positive scores, with some near undefeated performances. Decks i played angainst were like Labrynth, Mannadium or even Snake-Eyes. The deck's strength lies in its ability to survive the first turn and generate advantage through Draco monsters and disruptive plays with Summons, Protected by Diagram and Dreiath. With the help of cards like Strike of the Monarchs, the deck can navigate through opposing boards and build its own. Even though you could also play cards like Forbidden Droplet. Although it is not a top meta deck, i still recommend True Draco for its affordable price and personal enjoyment.

deck_excerpt: Pisa WCQ Qualifier 6th place Lorenzo Socci
deck_description:
Pisa WCQ Qualifier

6th place Lorenzo Socci

Is Tearlament still a good deck? Yes. Should you play it without the Horus cards? Better not. Nevertheless, here is a list without Horus. I've been playing this list for some time now and even though it lacks the consistency of the Horus cards, this deck can play very well without them. The Danger Monsters are there to guide the deck into plays as well as possible and with Nessie and 2 Destrudo we have easy ways to go into Baronne, for example, to enable fusion plays. If you want to play Guardian Chimera you should play KOTS plus Poly. I play the Shaddoll Engine more in the main, but since we want the maximum of good draws and mills, the Shaddoll Fusions are in the side for the fire match-ups. Bigfoot in the side deck represents the Going Second Danger monsters you could play. In my opinion one of the very good approaches of a non Horus version of Tear, but if you have the Horus cards you should play them.

deck_name: Rise of the True Dragon Structure Deck
deck_description:
The second half of 2016 is a season for Dragons in the Yu-Gi-Oh! TRADING CARD GAME! Following up on May’s re-launch of the legendary “Blue-Eyes” theme in Shining Victories, July brings more *oomph* to Duelists’ Dragon Decks with the Rise of the True Dragons Structure Deck!

This 41-card Deck is the second of four releases this year to celebrate the high-Level Dragon strategy pioneered by Seto Kaiba on the original Yu-Gi-Oh! animated TV series, and includes new high-Level Dragons that banish opposing cards when Summoned, and gain more Attack Points for each card they banish. Also included are new Dragon devotee monsters – easy-to-Summon low-Level Warriors that help get your high-Level Dragons into play quickly. The best part is that these utility Warriors work with ANY high-Level Dragons, including Dragons from other Decks and booster sets.

The real gem of Rise of the True Dragons Structure Deck is a new Spell Card that Summons any Level 7 or 8 Dragon directly from the Graveyard, with no restrictions, and can be used afterwards to protect your Dragons from being destroyed, with no drawbacks or limitations. A must-have card for every Dragon Deck!

Rise of the True Dragons Structure Deck contains a 41-card Deck with 2 Ultra Rares, 3 Super Rares, and 36 Commons, plus a new Dragon Token Card celebrating over a decade of devotion to Duelists’ Dragon Decks!

deck_description:
Quick labbing shows a weirdly neat consistency pick when it comes to Infernoid Evil and Dogmatika itself, mainly Dogmatikamatrix. 

Simply put: Send Evil to the graveyard after you setup a Dogmatika board going 1st with either Matrix or Macabre. 

Proceed for either Void Vanishment then into Void Feast or Void Blaze-Up to setup from there. 

This deck is still a WIP so change things as you wish.

deck_excerpt: Place counters on Spellcasters, summon more Spellcasters
deck_description:
The goal of this deck is to try and keep your opponent off resources, while using the different floaters and draw engines to ramp into a big otk push.

Apprentice Magician floats into a variety of maindeck toolbox monsters, getting you a tuner in Night's End Sorcerer, targeted destruction in Old Vindictive Magician, and draw power in Crystal Seer. It can also grab another copy of itself to thin the deck or load up the grave for Dark Armed Dragon.

Magical Exemplar is the heart of the deck, allowing you to summon Spellcasters from your hand or grave to reuse on summon or soft once per turn effects (Night's End Sorcerer, Kyco the Ghost Destroyer, Apprentice Magician, or Summoner Monk), summon a tuner for Synchro plays, or adjust your grave to help summon Dark Armed Dragon.

Mystic Tomato can you get into the Apprentice Magician engine, get you a level 2 or 3 tuner (Night's End Sorcerer, or Gale the Wirlwind), or get you Summoner Monk or Sangan.

Summoner Monk can get you Magical Exemplar, Breaker the Magical Warrior for targeted backrow removal, Kycoo the Ghost Destroyer to clear your opponent's grave, or Flamvell Magician to make a level 8 Synchro

To enable both Magical Exemplar and Summoner Monk, we're running an extensive spell line-up.

Brain Control, Mind Control, and Enemy Controller steal your opponent's monsters to clear their field or use as material.
Allure of Darkness, Upstart Goblin, and Foolish Burial let you dig deeper into your deck or find the cards you need.
Heavy Storm, Lightning Vortex, and Mystical Space Typhoon to clear your opponent's field.

Book of Moon and Shrink both fill double rolls: Shrink as a battle trick to survive or beat over your opponent's monsters, or to protect your summons from cards like Bottomless Trap Hole. Book of Moon to block your opponent from Synchro summoning or attacking into your key monsters, as well as reseting your own flip monsters.

This deck will be able to fight against other boss monsters, I have yet to decide which extra deck monsters would be good for this deck but I shall look around later.

 

The entire point of this deck is to just get kaijus out on your opponent's field and then utlize the kaiju counters provided depending on the kaijus. Danger engine is also in here to be used as big attack sticks and with their helpful effects, assist the kaijus to clear the board. They also provide gas as well so bricking with this should not be often.

 

I am thinking about putting XYZ monsters or Link Monsters into this deck to make use of the levels or the amount of monsters but that would seem to be more challenging than anticipated.

 

Thank you.

deck_excerpt: Don't pay $1000s for fire, pay $100 for water instead.
deck_description:
It's time to go fishing with the power of the white fish(and space fish). The new white aura support cards have added a new dimension to the ghoti playstyle, allowing for easy access to the ghoti line and a sweep of powerful water ED monsters. In this discription I will give a card by card and at the end i will give an example of a standard line. 

Icejade Ran Aegirine: Pitch a water to access any link 2 or synchro 10. typically a backup plan if your board is Nibirued, though it does put fish into the GY for white mirror. 

Ghoti lineup: the reason for playing 1 of each of the good ghotis is because through the white monsters you get easy access to Arionpos who gets any of the ghoti rotation banished. The ghotis on their own don't facilitate much so you dont want to max out on basically any of them but you want at least 1 of each name for setups. Drawing them is not that big of an issue since alot of the deck is extenders so wasting a normal on Shif doesnt feel that bad. Remember, ghotis also play on both players turns. 

Abyss shark: extender, searches basically your entire deck, whats not to like?

Lifeless Leaffish: the best normal summon in the deck. sends shif who then banishes itself to setup for your opponents turn and recovers and draws in the GY. And to head off any questions about why no beatunaful princess, you already have plenty of ways to search leafless so no point in wasting your normal on ash bait. plus no monster on board means you cant use abyss sharks eff.

White stingray: Honestly the cuttable member of the white lineup but I like it since it can setup some dead ghotis in hand by pitching them and is a fine target for white mirror. but still its very cuttable. 

White Sunfish and White Sardines: The stars of the show(no offense to the ghotis). Sardine pitches another of itself from the deck FOR COST to summon itself and sunfish can summon itself and another fish in the GY if you control a monster with the same name. So basically pitch sardine, summon sardine, target sardine with sunfish, summon itself and summon sardine in GY that then becomes a tuner. I'll get into more of the combo later but one thing i'll end on is that all the white aura monsters can become tuners if summoned from the GY. 

White Reincarnation: Searches any of the white monsters. Its other 2 effects arent really important since you arent trying to end on the White aura synchros, but they can be usful effects if you have to tunnel into a white aura line for the sake of boardbreaking and OTKs.

White Mirror: Monster reborn for any of the Level 4 or lower fish while also searching another copy from your deck(thought this does mean it can be ashed.)

Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign: Usually you are making this off Icejade Ran, though its matchup dependent. It's banish effect can trigger when you banish ghotis or for ghoti effects so you could banish alot off a normal ghoti combo. 

Icejade Gymir: The prefered summon off icejade ran when going first. Its quick effect is both protection and removal if you chain it to an opponents card activation. And it can bring itself back when your opponent banishes something. 

Ghoti of the Deep Beyond: The boss of the ghotis. Massive board nuke and brings itself back as a big boi. Pretty standard stuff.

Ravenour Crocosaurus: There is a simple line with Sardines + abyss shark that lets you make this with 3 materials netting you a draw 2. Can be very useful to get out of sticky hands and can TECHNICALLY be ghoti quick synchro into though the board setup is pretty suspect. 

Adamancipater Dragite: Standard Water boss monster. Just a Free spell/trap negate.

White Aura Whale: Helps with clearing boards and is pretty useful for OTKs with reincarnation up. Both Whale and Porpoise bring themselves back when destroyed by banishing another fish in the GY(I.e. Ghotis) and thats not once per turn so you could keep bringing them back. 

Askaan, The Bicorned Ghoti: Ghotis TRUE boss monster. When summoned, banishes itself and another card on field, then banishes a fish in the GY to bring itself back. The main monster you go into during your opponents turn as interaction and to banish the ghoti used for its summon. 

Arionpos: The cetral playmaker for the deck. Banishes any fish from your deck and when used as synchro material, banishes a fish to search a fish with equal or lower level. I could list a number of uses for this card but that would be its own page so to sum it up, this card is GOOD.

White Aura Porpoise: On summon, brings back any fish and if you have another copy in the GY, brings that back too. Can be very useful for synchro laddering.

Coral Anemone: Easy to make, and can be extension by bringing back the lower Atk fish. Has allowed the deck to play through multiple disruptions and still have access to Arionpos. 

Abyss keeper: Extender to get dead ghotis out of the hand and can also be removal. 

Number 4: Stealth Kragen: Its actually easy to make Kragen in this deck since Abyss shark treats itself as a 4 if used for the XYZ summon of a number monster. Just another piece of removal.

TY-PHON: Honestly a flex slot and can be anything. Little knight if you are rich, Worldsea dragon for cleaning up boardstates. You get locked into Waters pretty frequently so generic good stuff is few and far between.

I think this deck can be pretty competitive and has play around most handtraps. Ash is nothing, droll can be played through with the White Auras, even D-shifter isnt that great since ghotis are used to playing banished. The main handtrap that has been an issue for me is Nibiru and the main way to play around it is to end on a mid-power board, let them nib, then use icejade ran or normal summon leaffish(yes you can do an entire combo line without normal summoning once).

Heres a combo line with Sardines and Abyss Shark:

Special Sardines(sending another to the GY from deck), activate Abyss shark summoning itself and searching sunfish. Use sunfish to bring itself out and bring back the Sardine in the GY, making it a tuner. Use the tuner Sardine and the Sunfish to make arionpos. Use Arionpos to banish Paces. Use Shark and the other Sardine to make coral anemone. Bring back either Sardines or Sunfish, make either a tuner, then use Arionpos and either tuner to make Dragite or Supreme Sovereing respectively. Use Arionpos second effect, banish itself, search leaffish. Normal Leaffish, use its effect to send Shif. Banish Shif to increase ATK(though this part doesnt matter). During your opponets standby, Paces and Shif both comeback and you have quickplay access to the arionpos-Askaan-Deep line all on your opponents turn. 

Feel free to ask questions about ratios and other potential lines in the comments.

Branded despia deck
A deck thats a little bit serious but still mostly built for fun

Step into the eerie realm of the undead with the spine-chilling Skull Servant Deck! Unearth the power of the shadows as you assemble an army of bone-chilling skeletons to strike fear into the hearts of your opponents.

My rendition of Atlantean Mermail. The deck is still a 1 card OTK with Deep Sea Diva, but this is my expanded version of it where in theory you can do more things before OTK'ing. 

Coral Anemone is probably the best bridge/recycler in the deck. Needing no specific statlines to summon, you make her with any two Water monsters but she gives you access to just about anything you need. You will be summoning back Neptabyss or Heavy Infantry for the majority of the time, Neptabyss usually to tribute it with Abyssmegalo to then revive Dragoons, reviving Heavy Infantry can let you get a second normal summon so if you have a second Deep Sea Diva you can continue your combo then. 

Minairuka is one of my new favorite cards in water decks after testing it out, its ability on the field is basically non-existent but serves instead as a way to chain block your important cards from being ashed. Normal Deep Sea Diva, activate effect of DSD then chain Minairuka as CL2 to protect her from Ash Blossom. It really is more or less just Ash "Insurance" but comes up so much more often than I ever thought it would. Also serves as a good body on the field to make Dweller using it and Dragoons then triggering Dragoons again.

Icejade Ran Aegirine is another good starter despite it locking you into waters while you control that token, since you make Icejade Gymir Aegirine, Chengying, or Coral Anemone with her and the token. It's essentially the 2023-24 version of Abyssteus but better. 

There's an unbelievable amount of lines the deck can cycle through but due to the extremely linear gameplan the deck has always had you should expect to lose more than you win in Best of 1 scenarios. The deck lives and dies by the side-deck since every interruption since 2017 has basically corkscrewed the entire gameplan. Even a well timed Veiler can completely kill the objective of playing Atlantean Mermail. 

But overall this is the version i'm happy with, the right amount of utility and thinning, the ability to chainblock, strong bosses still makeable (Baronne, Cheng, Gymir, Dragite) and of course the fact that it's still Atlantean Mermail- the deck excels in getting the job done and the game over as good as it did when Neptabyss came out.

Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament: Dublin WCQ Regional – March 10th 2024

Placement: Top 8

Domain Format requires your deck to have 60 cards in the main deck instead of the usual minimum of 40. You can only run 1 copy of each card in your deck (So you can't play 3 Blue-Eyes White Dragons for example), and you must have a Deck Master, a Monster that exists outside of the Main or Extra deck, meaning it doesn't count to the 60 card main deck limit or 15 card extra deck limit.

Your Deck Master determines what other monsters you can play in your deck, depending on it's Type, Attribute, and affiliations with Archetypes aswell as specific cards listed in it's text. If it mentions a Type, Attribute or specific ATK/DEF line (Like 2400ATK/1000 DEF for example) in it's text, you can also include those kinds of monsters in your deck.

Deck Masters can be summoned from the Deck Master Zone using their appropriate mechanic (Normal Summon, Tribute Summon, Synchro Summon, etc...) or by using their Inherent Summon effect if your chosen Deck Master has one (An inherent summon is any kind of monster effect that allows the card to special summon itself to the field without starting a chain, easily identifiable by the lack of a ":" or ";" in the effect).

Deck Masters can be returned to the Deck Master Zone if they get sent from the field to any other zone, like the graveyard or banishment.

You must pay a cumulative cost of 500 life points to summon your Deck Master for each time it has returned to the Deck Master Zone. (1st: 500 LP, 2nd: 1,000 LP, 3rd: 1500 LP, etc...)

deck_excerpt: Fossil Fusion and Gem-Knights combine for some strong grind game.
deck_description:
The deck master Gem-Armadillo can search Brilliant Rose for an easy Phantom Quartz. The other prefered target is regular Quartz to find Scatter Fusion which plays better than Brilliant Fusion due to it's reusablity. If you have Painful Choice on the first turn the targets are Crystal, 1 other normal Gem-Knight, Lazuli, Gem-Knight Fusion, and Weathering Soldier. If you're on the other side of this Lazuli is unfortunately the least value to give, and I still get access to both fusion spells. Build towards a big Dimension Fusion (or Return from the Different Dimension) and end the game!
Gem-Turtle is an easy cut if you want to slip in another card, but considering the Pyramid Turtle and UFO Turtle memes it's here as an alternative deck master.

deck_excerpt: Unleash powerful plants and towering extra deck monsters using this fertilized deck!
deck_description: I've been running sylvans since 2014 and have been tweaking this deck little by little over time. This is my current version that I have been having a lot of fun with and wanted to share. It has many different ways to go into Link 4s, Rank 7-9's, and synchro as well however you must be aware of the Rikka cards plant locking you. The little micro engines of each sub archtype seem to work just well with the Sylvan plant excavation system however this does mean there is some RNG when it comes to this deck. I hope that you all enjoy this build and can perhaps suggest any tips for making this deck even tighter.

Deck is made up of cards I had laying around. Extra deck could be better. Dark Doriado isn't just for the attributes in this deck. It can be your set up to stack your top 4 with a Kaiju or set up to do the main combo of summoning the Awakening of the Possessed monsters using their effects and then linking them off for the link monsters in order to search a possessed spell or trap card. Dark Doriado is also important because when you activate it in the pendulum scale it buffs Earth, Fire, Wind, and Water monsters by 200 for each different attribute.

deck_excerpt: Made using only cards from OTS 1 Tournament Pack.
deck_description:
- Infernoid Patrulea and Mezuki have to target their effects on other copies of themselves since there are no Infernoids or Zombies on OTS 1 (except from Skull Servant). 
- Use Performapals to draw cards.

Deck made using only OTS 1 Packs (2024 banlist).

I tried it out and it worked. You have to be careful because some effects prevents you from special summoning monsters other than zombie (es. Eldlixir of Scarlet Sanguine ) or synchro and fusion monsters (es. Earthbound Prisoner Stone Sweeper  and Harmonic Synchro Fusion ). You also want Cursed Eldland  to leave the field as fast as possible once you have Eldlich the Golden Lord  on the field (es. discard cards like ultimate earthbound or a golden land and activate the special summon from the graveyard tributing cursed eldland) because having it on the field prevents you from attacking with your earthbound monsters.
02-01-003-00 → Dragon/Red-Eyes
